            <section class="mt-8 prose">
              <h2>What this scrapbooking calculator does</h2>
              <p>
                This scrapbooking calculator is designed for practical, everyday
                use at your craft table. It helps you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Check how many photos and mats will fit on a page.</li>
                <li>
                  See how much of the page is used vs. left for journaling and
                  embellishments.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Plan how many mats or panels you can cut from a full sheet of
                  paper.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Switch between inches and centimeters without re‑doing the
                  math.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How the layout calculation works</h2>
              <p>
                The calculator treats your photos (plus optional mats) as
                rectangles arranged in a simple grid. You choose how many photos
                per row, and it computes how many rows you need.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Step 1 – Mat size (if used)</p>
                <p>
                  If you add a mat border of size \(b\) around a photo of width
                  \(w\) and height \(h\):
                </p>
                <p>\[ w_\text{mat} = w + 2b,\quad h_\text{mat} = h + 2b \]</p>
                <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">Step 2 – Grid dimensions</p>
                <p>With <em>N</em> photos and <em>C</em> photos per row:</p>
                <p>\[ \text{rows} = \left\lceil \frac{N}{C} \right\rceil \]</p>
                <p>Horizontal span (including spacing \(s\)):</p>
                <p>
                  \[ W_\text{layout} = C \cdot w_\text{mat} + (C - 1)\cdot s \]
                </p>
                <p>Vertical span:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ H_\text{layout} = \text{rows} \cdot h_\text{mat} +
                  (\text{rows} - 1)\cdot s \]
                </p>
                <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">Step 3 – Page fit</p>
                <p>With page width \(W_p\), height \(H_p\) and margin \(m\):</p>
                <p>
                  \[ W_\text{usable} = W_p - 2m,\quad H_\text{usable} = H_p - 2m
                  \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  If \(W_\text{layout} \le W_\text{usable}\) and
                  \(H_\text{layout} \le H_\text{usable}\), the layout fits.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>How the cutting planner works</h2>
              <p>
                The cutting planner assumes straight cuts in a grid pattern. It
                calculates how many pieces of a given size you can cut from a
                full sheet, optionally leaving a trim margin around the edges.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Effective sheet size</p>
                <p>
                  With sheet width \(W_s\), height \(H_s\) and trim margin
                  \(t\):
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ W_\text{eff} = W_s - 2t,\quad H_\text{eff} = H_s - 2t \]
                </p>
                <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">Pieces per sheet</p>
                <p>For piece width \(w\) and height \(h\):</p>
                <p>
                  \[ n_x = \left\lfloor \frac{W_\text{eff}}{w}
                  \right\rfloor,\quad n_y = \left\lfloor \frac{H_\text{eff}}{h}
                  \right\rfloor \]
                </p>
                <p>\[ N_\text{pieces} = n_x \times n_y \]</p>
                <p>
                  The calculator also tries the rotated orientation (swap \(w\)
                  and \(h\)) and shows which yields more pieces.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Tips for using this tool effectively</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Start with your photos.</strong> Enter the exact print
                  size (e.g., 3×4, 4×6) before adding mats.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Leave realistic margins.</strong> Most scrapbookers
                  prefer at least 0.5 in (or 1–1.5 cm) around the page edge.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use spacing to avoid crowding.</strong> Even 0.25–0.5
                  in between photos can make a layout feel more balanced.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use the cutting planner for batches.</strong> If
                  you’re making multiple identical pages or cards, it will tell
                  you how many sheets you need.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Common use cases</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Planning a 12×12 layout with multiple 4×6 photos and
                  journaling blocks.
                </li>
                <li>Designing pocket pages with 3×4 and 4×6 cards.</li>
                <li>
                  Cutting card fronts and layers from 8.5×11 or A4 cardstock.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Batch‑cutting photo mats for a mini album or wedding guest
                  book.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>Can I use this for card making or mini albums?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Any project that uses rectangular pages and pieces works.
                For example, set the page size to 4.25×5.5 in for an A2 card
                front, or to your mini album page size, then enter your panel
                sizes as “photos.”
              </p>

              <h3>Does this calculator handle circles or shaped photos?</h3>
              <p>
                Not directly. The math assumes rectangles, but you can still use
                the tool to estimate how many circular elements will fit by
                using their bounding box (e.g., a 3 in circle as 3×3 in).
              </p>

              <h3>How do I estimate how many sheets of paper I need?</h3>
              <p>
                Use the cutting planner to find how many pieces you can cut from
                one sheet. Then divide the total number of pieces you need by
                that number and round up to the next whole sheet.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I save or print my layout?</h3>
              <p>
                This calculator focuses on fast planning and math. For printable
                sketches or digital layouts, you can transfer the dimensions
                into your favorite design tool or sketch them on graph paper
                using the measurements provided.
              </p>
